2 LLM Architecture Components Contributing to Vulnerabilities
LLMs are characterized by extensive parameter sizes and intelligent learning capabilities [138]. The model is pre-trained with a large dataset containing public Internet data, books, and various texts to learn a language’s underlying structures, patterns, and contextual relationships. The foundational component of LLMs, shared by numerous LLMs, including GPT-3 [58], InstructGPT [150], Llama 3 [50], and GPT-4 [3], is the self-attention mechanism [206] in the Transformer architecture. It plays a major role in the landscape of NLP by efficiently managing sequential data, facilitating parallelization, and capturing long-range dependencies in text data. During pre-training, the input text is tokenized and processed by the model through the Transformer architecture. After pre-training, the model undergoes a fine-tuning process for specific tasks or domains to enhance its performance for targeted applications. The model then generates output (e.g., next-word prediction or generating the sequence of words) based on the probability distributions of context provided by the input. In-context learning is a major feature of LLMs, in which the model can learn from a given context or prompt to generate text without further training. This capability allows LLMs to produce more coherent and contextually relevant responses, which are ideal for interactive conversational applications, such as chatbots. LLMs are trained on a vast amount of data; however, they might still lack unforeseen task-specific data. LLMs are also equipped with few-shot learning [17], where the model is trained on a limited number of instances per class to provide accurate predictions. Despite having limited training data, this method enables the model to perform well in terms of generalization to new or unknown cases. Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) [275] is an additional critical aspect of LLMs. This approach involves enhancing the LLM’s capability through Reinforcement Learning (RL), utilizing humangenerated responses, and enabling the model to learn from errors and enhance its performance progressively. The most prevalent interaction strategy with LLMs involves prompt engineering [35, 226, 272], where users create and provide specific instructions to LLMs through the prompt to generate desired responses and perform particular tasks. This approach is extensively embraced in current evaluation initiatives, allowing users to interact with LLMs through question-and-answer engagement [89]. Various components and entities in LLM architecture, such as end users, developers, training/fine-tuning data, and the deployed model, can contribute to vulnerabilities in LLMs.
