3 Overview of LLM Vulnerabilities, Potential Mitigation, Challenges, and Future Research
In recent studies, the vulnerabilities and challenges of LLMs have been categorized in different directions. Several security and privacy risks and vulnerabilities, including misinformation [153], trustworthiness [122], and hallucinations [132], are prevalent in LLMs. In existing studies, the classification of security and privacy attacks followed either the goal-based approach or method-based approach. The basic idea behind security is to safeguard the system, which involves preventing unauthorized access, modification, malfunctioning, or denial of service to authorized users during normal usage [21]. Privacy refers to protecting personal information by controlling individual access to their personal information in a system [36]. In this article, we devote our efforts to investigating vulnerabilities of LLMs from two main perspectives: security and privacy, using the goal-based approach. Regarding security risks, we primarily focus on the following categories and subcategories. Each category is further detailed in Section 4:
— Prompt Hacking (Section 4.1): Prompt Injection (Section 4.1.1), Jailbreaking Attacks (Section 4.1.2) — Adversarial Attacks (Section 4.2): Backdoor Attacks (Section 4.2.1), Data Poisoning Attacks (Section 4.2.2)
We also discuss three representative categories of privacy attacks as follows:
— Gradient Leakage Attacks (Section 5.1)
— Membership Inference Attacks (MIAs) (Section 5.2) — PII Leakage Attacks (Section 5.3)
In our analysis, we observed that different attack categories can share common goals from security and privacy perspectives, such as backdoor and poisoning attacks aiming to cause malfunctioning in an AI system [184, 244]. Again, prompt injection [187] and jailbreaking attacks [221] share the common goal of misleading LLMs to obtain sensitive information by generating deceiving prompts [183]. Figure 4 represents a summary of common LLM vulnerabilities, different types of security and privacy attacks, corresponding mitigation techniques, challenges, and future research directions. The instances pointed out by blue arrows indicate potentially shared goals across different types of attack methods and defense techniques. We elaborate this analysis in the rest of the article.
