Since the introduction of LLMs, various endeavors have often revolved around finding innovative ways to prompt and interact with LLMs to explore their capabilities, uncover potential vulnerabilities, and, most importantly, ensure responsible and ethical use. This section will discuss some representative types of security vulnerabilities aimed at producing inappropriate content or malfunctioning LLM systems. In Figure 5, we show different categories of security attacks in LLMs with their examples. Additionally, we demonstrate their characteristics, limitations, and potential mitigation techniques of the corresponding security attacks in Table 2.
4.1 Prompt Hacking
As LLMs work with interaction-based question and answering systems with their users, they need to put specific queries to the prompt, then it generates outputs based on training. Prompt hacking manipulates the input prompts of the LLM to obtain the desired output by a malicious user. With proper malicious prompts, even a well-trained model can produce misleading or malicious content [140]. The two types of goal-based prompt hacking strategies are described next.
4.1.1 Prompt Injection. Prompt injection entails bypassing LLM safety filters by manipulating the model with meticulously crafted prompts that cause the model to disregard the original prompt. It may cause unintended consequences, such as data leakage, unauthorized access, and hate speech generation [173]. Recent studies explored several prompt injection attacks in LLMs. A straightforward way to mislead an LLM is to instruct it to ignore the previous prompt. This method is a combination of goal hijacking and prompt leaking [156]. Goal hijacking (also known as “Prompt Divergence” [180]) is defined as the manipulation of the original prompt goal to mislead the model to generate a specific target phrase. In prompt leaking, the original prompt goal is redirected to the objective of reproducing the partial or entire original prompt. Perez and Ribeiro [156] performed an early study on prompt injection attacks, considering 35 different application scenarios built on OpenAI models. Their research explored two primary attack types: goal hijacking and prompt leaking. They named their method “Ignore previous prompt (PromptInject).” Liu et al. [121] introduced HOUYI, a black-box prompt injection attack method inspired by traditional web injection attacks, which reveals previously undiscovered and significant attack consequences. It explores vulnerabilities through unrestricted arbitrary LM usage and simple theft of application prompts [121] on GPT-3. Kang et al. [98] introduced a template that considers the programmatic capabilities of instruction-following LLMs, which can potentially generate malicious content (e.g., hate speech and scams) without additional training or prompt engineering. While several studies focused on manual prompt injection techniques, Shin et al. [187] introduced an automated approach, AutoPrompt, employing a gradient-guided search strategy to obtain an efficient prompt template for diverse tasks. AutoPrompt-generated prompts extract more accurate factual knowledge from Masked Language Models (MLMs) than manually crafted prompts in the LAMA benchmark [166]. However, AutoPrompt was not evaluated on
