The existing research on the jailbreaking attack is primarily focused on evaluating the efficacy of malicious prompts that manipulate LLMs to generate inappropriate/harmful content [94]. In these studies [183, 253], jailbreaking prompts were collected from diverse platforms and websites (e.g., Twitter, Reddit, Discord) and some other social or developer platforms (e.g., Jailbreaking site [6]). Li et al. [112] proposed a method named DeepInception, which leverages the personification and instruction following ability of LLMs [223]. It hypnotizes the LLMs by asking them to respond to a harmful query in a nested fashion to bypass the LLM’s basic safety alignments [112]. The pioneer in jailbreaking attacks is proposed by Shen et al. [183], known as “DAN” (Do Anything Now). It leverages the instruction following the character “DAN” that pre-trains the model to generate outputs starting with it. Studies have been done in various directions to perform jailbreaking attacks using tricky prompts that are able to generate such inappropriate contents as mentioned earlier in widely known LLMs (e.g., GPT 3.5) [219]. There are several jailbreaking datasets with jailbreaking prompts [229] with the potential to bypass the security measures of ChatGPT to generate inappropriate content. Again, several patterns of generating jailbreaking prompts are prevalent in the literature, such as pretending, attention shifting, and privilege escalation [124]. Wei et al. [221] presented two failure modes in LLM safety against jailbreaking attacks. The first is competing objective, which conflicts between model capabilities, such as the directive to “always follow instructions,” and safety goals. It includes prefix injection and refusal suppression. The second is mismatched generalization, where safety training does not work for generalizing to a domain where the necessary capabilities exist. Additionally, under context contamination [180], the safety training of the LLM may be compromised. Once the model is jailbroken (i.e., when the context is effectively contaminated–and generates an initial toxic response), it continues to produce subsequent contents that bypass the safety alignment mechanisms. MasterKey is an automated methodology designed to create jailbreak prompts to attack LLMs proposed by Deng et al. [44]. Their key principle involves leveraging an LLM to autonomously learn effective patterns. Lapid et al. [106] proposed a method that utilizes a genetic algorithm to influence LLMs when the architecture and parameters of the model are not accessible. Combining the adversarial prompt with the user’s query misleads the targeted model and leads to unintended and adversarial outputs [106]. Several methods have been proposed to perform automatic jailbreaking by leveraging the advantage of low resources of language or clever role-playing techniques, such as GPTfuzz [252] and AutoDAN [118]. Despite the significant computational cost, these methods illustrated a high jailbreaking success rate without including additional prompts. Chu et al. [34] presented a systematic benchmark for 13 state-of-the-art jailbreaking attacks of different approaches on several of the most popular LLMs. Recent studies focused on jailbreaking attacks in multi-modal settings. For instance, Qi et al. [161] showed a concrete illustration of the risks involved by demonstrating how visual adversarial examples can effectively jailbreak LLMs that integrate visual input. Inspired by the LLMs’ step-by-step reasoning capability [101], recently, a jailbreaking method known as Multi-Step
