Here, η is an adversarial perturbation sample added to the training data, which aims to manipulate the label to an incorrect one (f (x), y′) or a specified one (f (x ′) = y′) [257]. Figure 7 illustrates the overview of adversarial attacks. For the benign case, a normal user asks a question to the LLM via a prompt. The LLM generates the response and shows it to the user. When the LLM is maliciously prompted (instructs the LLM to ignore the previous prompt), it would show the response the malicious user wants (the red portions). In the following, we discuss existing representative types of adversarial attacks.
4.2.1 Backdoor Attack. Backdoor attacks in LLMs refer to the insertion of hidden backdoors/triggering tokens that make the model function normally on benign samples but ineffectively on poisoned samples. The backdoors/triggering tokens involve malicious modifications to prompts, compromising the model so that it can generate malicious outputs by associating specific prompts with desired output [264]. Cai et al. [18] introduced BadPrompt, a backdoor attack method that targets continuous prompts to attack, which contains two modules: trigger candidate generation and adaptive trigger optimization for the most efficient one. A backdoor was reported on RL fine-tuning in LMs called BadGPT by Shi et al. [184], where they utilized a backdoor trigger word “CF” to manipulate the model’s output on sentiment analysis. ProAttack is an effective approach for executing clean-label backdoor attacks relying on the prompt itself as a trigger that does not need external triggers [264]. A more realistic clean-label attack called
