Privacy risks in LLMs arise from their inherent capacity to process and generate text based on extensive and diverse training datasets. These models (e.g., GPT-3) may inadvertently capture and reproduce sensitive information that exists in training data, potentially posing privacy concerns during the text generation process. Data memorization, data leakage, and the potential disclosure of confidential information or PII are key challenges [152] in LLM privacy protection. In Figure 8, we show the categories of privacy attacks in LLMs with some examples. Further, in Table 3, we present the LLM privacy attack categories, source codes, their characteristics, limitations, and potential mitigation techniques. In the corresponding subsections, we discuss these further in detail.
5.1 Gradient Leakage Attack
In DNNs, gradients represent the direction of the steepest increase in a function that helps to optimize model parameters during training to minimize the loss function. Several studies (e.g., [42, 64, 224, 273]) have shown that private training samples can be successfully reconstructed from the deep learning model using gradients with high reconstruction accuracy under the Federated Learning (FL) environment. However, these methods work mostly for image datasets. In LMs/LLMs, sensitive information can be extracted by analyzing gradients during their training or fine-tuning phase. One of the early explorations of gradient leakage attacks against LMs is gradient-based distributional attack, which performs gradient-based text attacks on Transformers [67]. It leverages parameterized adversarial distribution to enable gradient optimization to perform efficient gradient leakage attacks instead of using a single adversarial instance. This attack is effective for different LMs on distinct tasks. Deng et al. [45] introduced a universal gradient attack on Transformer-based LMs in the NLP domain, named TAG. TAG can reconstruct the private training samples, (X , Y ), from Transformer-based LMs [45]. The TAG adversary acquires gradients ∇W from a participant in a distributed learning system, then updates randomly initialized dummy data (X0, Y0) through a comparison of the difference between acquired gradients ∇W (from clients) and the adversary’s gradients ∇W0 by leveraging a loss function. The LAMP attack is a technique designed for recovering input text from gradients in an FL environment proposed by Balunovic et al. [11]. It utilizes an auxiliary LM to guide the search process toward generating
