5.2 Membership Inference Attack
The primary goal of an MIA is to determine if a data sample has been included in an ML model’s training data [52]. MIA poses serious privacy concerns, particularly in scenarios where the targeted
ACM Comput. Surv., Vol. 57, No. 6, Article 152. Publication date: February 2025.


Security and Privacy Challenges of Large Language Models: A Survey 152:15
model has undergone training on sensitive information, such as medical or financial data [203]. Shokri et al. [188] first introduced MIA-ML, the MIA against ML model. The attack model is trained through their proposed shadow training technique: first, several “shadow” models are constructed to mirror the behavior of the target model, where the training dataset is known, and thus so is the ground truth about the membership. Then, the attack model is trained on the labeled (member/nonmember) inputs and outputs from the shadow models to classify whether a given sample is a member of the training data. Existing privacy attacks against LMs through MIA are mainly focused on text generation and downstream text classification tasks [182, 192]. Xin et al. [238] took the first initiative to perform a systematic audit of the privacy risks associated with Pre-trained Language Models (PLMs) by focusing on the perspective of MIA. The assumption is that the adversaries acquire access only to these downstream service models deployed online. Furthermore, they considered another more realistic scenario where no additional information about the target PLMs (BERT, ALBERT, RoBERTa, and XLNet) is available to the adversary other than the output (i.e., black-box setting). Mireshghallah et al. [139] reported that previous attacks on MLMs (e.g., [99, 120]) may have yielded inconclusive results due to their exclusive reliance on the loss of the target model on individual samples for the evaluation of how effectively the model memorized those samples. In these attacks, if the loss falls below a threshold, the sample is flagged as a potential training set member. Jagannatha et al. [87] investigated the risks of training data leakage to estimate the empirical privacy leaks for model architectures such as BERT [47] and GPT-2 [162]. Kaneko et al. [97] proposed a sampling-based pseudo-likelihood method for MIA. They call it SaMIA. It can detect the membership of a given text in the training data of an LLM without accessing the model’s likelihood or loss values. SaMIA generates multiple text samples from the LLM during testing and calculates the n-gram overlap between the samples and the target text. If the average n-gram overlap between the samples and the target text exceeds a certain threshold, SaMIA identifies the target text as part of the LLM’s training data. Feng et al. [55] introduced PREMIA (Preference data MIA) to analyze the vulnerability of using preference data in LLM alignment to MIAs. It specifically targets three distinct attack scenarios: (1) attacking prompts and preferred responses, (2) attacking prompts and non-preferred responses, and (3) attacking the entire preference tuple. Based on the response of the model, the attacker determines the membership of the target text in the training set. For training the attack models [188], MIAs are based on a highly optimistic and arguably unrealistic assumption in many cases that an adversary knows the distribution of training data of the target model [249]. Further, SaMIA [97] was evaluated only on a single task—classification—and its performance on other tasks, such as translation or text generation, may not achieve similar effectiveness. Moreover, the method was tested on public training data WikiMIA [186]. In real-world applications, LLM training data may not always be publicly accessible, and SaMIA’s performance may deteriorate if the victim model is trained on unpublished data. However, PREMIA [55] was evaluated on open source LLMs, and its performance may not be consistent on closed source models such as GPT-3. In general, MIA can be defended at both the training/fine-tuning phase and the inference phase of the target model. Various techniques to defend the LMs against MIA have been proposed, such as regularization, transfer learning, and information perturbation [78, 96]. However, it is not sufficient from all the perspectives of MIA in LMs. The techniques proposed for LMs can potentially be applied to LLMs. However, further extensive research is needed to evaluate the severity of attacks in LLMs and the impact of existing mitigation techniques.
5.3 PII Leakage Attack
PII refers to data that can uniquely identify an individual, either alone or combined with other information [59]. Sensitive PII includes information, such as name, phone number, address, Social
ACM Comput. Surv., Vol. 57, No. 6, Article 152. Publication date: February 2025.


152:16 B. C. Das et al.
Security Number (SSN), financial records, and medical records. In LLMs, PII leakage has been a fundamental problem. In March 2023, it was reported that ChatGPT leaked users’ conversation history as well as information related to payment due to a system bug [102]. Evidence has been found about information leakage through sentence-level MIA [188] and reconstruction attacks on private training data [267]. One of the early studies of the PII leakage attack, named TAB [86], investigated whether the model could reveal user content from the training set when it was presented with the relevant context. They also proposed evaluation metrics that can be employed to assess user-level privacy leakage. Lukas et al. [125] empirically demonstrated that their proposed attack method against the GPT-2 model can extract up to 10× more PII sequences than the TAB attack. PII reconstruction and record-level membership inference were shown to have a subtle relationship [125]. Zanella-Béguelin et al. [254] explored the impact of updates on LMs by analyzing snapshots before and after an update, revealing insights into changes in training data. Moreover, they introduced two metrics, differential score and differential rank, to assess data leakage in natural LMs. ProPILE was introduced as a tool for PII leakage in LLM and experimented on open pre-trained Transformer LMs (OPT-1.3B model [255]). It will ask for a specific PII, such as a personal contact number or SSN, in the designed LLM prompt by providing relevant information. Then, the LLM response may provide the requested information based on the linkability of the given information and the structure of the crafted prompt [100]. A universal PII leakage framework named KART has been introduced specifically for the biomedical domain [142]. Nakka et al. [143] proposed a PII leakage attack, termed PII-compass, by adding hand-crafted template to an attack prefix. These attack prefixes are associated with a different data subject from the adversary set, meaning that the data (attack prefix) used to create the new prompt originates from a different data subject whose PII is intended for extraction. Memorization is another aspect of PII attacks. Carlini et al. [20] demonstrated that LLMs memorize and leak individual training examples. They showed how a malicious party may query the LM (e.g., GPT-2) to execute a training data extraction attack and get specific training samples. Furthermore, several investigations revealed that PLMs have a high probability of disclosing private and confidential data, particularly when prompted for information such as e-mail addresses along with their contexts that include the owner’s name. PLMs retain personal data, which means that the data may be retrieved using a certain prefix, such as training data tokens. PLMs link the owner of the personal information to it, thus attackers may query the data using the owner’s identity [81]. Several shortcomings exist in the PII leakage attacks prevalent in the literature. For instance, Huang et al. [81] primarily focused on extracting e-mail addresses as representatives of personal information in their proposed memorization attack in PLM. On the contrary, PII-compass [143] is limited to only extracting phone numbers. Complete extraction of a PII set still requires significant exploration and proper methods. While some methods have been evaluated only on small Transformer-based LMs [86], others have been tested on earlier LLMs such as GPT-2 [20]. The performance of these methods (e.g., [81, 86]) on the latest LLMs, such as Llama 3 and GPT-4, still requires in-depth evaluation. Moreover, some of these methods may not perform well in the presence of defense mechanisms such as DP [1]. Thus, further research is necessary to develop attack methods that address these challenges in PII leakage attacks against LLMs.
