6.1 Defense against Security Attacks on LLMs
Defense against Prompt Injection. Limited studies explored the defense strategy against prompt injection attacks in LLMs. A prevention/detection-based defense technique has been reported to systematically present existing defense mechanisms against prompt injection attacks [121]. Prevention-based defenses, as outlined in the work of Jain et al. [88], are designed to thwart the successful execution of tasks injected into an LLM-integrated application. These preventive measures involve pre-processing the data prompt to eliminate the injected task’s instruction/data and/or redesigning the instruction prompt itself. To thwart adversarial prompts, there are several techniques, such as paraphrasing [88], re-tokenization [88], data prompt isolation, and instructional prevention [171]. Paraphrasing disrupts the sequence of injected data, such as injected instructions and special character insertion. Re-tokenization aims to break the sequence of injected instructions, task-ignoring text, special characters, and fake responses within a compromised data prompt. This disruption diminishes the efficacy of prompt injection attacks. Detection-based defenses are focused on determining the integrity of a given data prompt [88, 190, 215]. Notably, the proactive detection method [175] has proven effective in identifying instances of prompt injection attacks. Perplexity-based detection is a kind of prompt-based detection. The idea is to add information or instructions to a data prompt, which degrades its quality and leads to increased perplexity. Consequently, a data prompt is considered to be compromised if its perplexity exceeds a specified threshold [66]. Since an LLM-integrated application is tailored for a specific task, granting it prior knowledge of the anticipated response, detecting a compromised data prompt is feasible when the generated response deviates from the proper answer for the desired task [175]. For example, if the desired task is spam detection and the response does not align with “spam” or “non-spam,” they imply a compromise. Notably, this defense is ineffective when the injected task and desired task share the same type (e.g., both being related to spam detection). Effective protection strategies against P2SQL injection attacks are available and may be incorporated into the LangChain framework as extensions [155]. For example, since P2SQL injection attacks can manipulate chatbots by arbitrarily executing different queries [155], controlling database roles and permissions to limit the execution of undesired SQL statements when accessing tables with sensitive information can be a viable technique to defend such attacks. Conversely, indirect attacks involve malicious input residing in the database, enabling interference with LLM-generated SQL queries and potentially undermining the effectiveness of these defenses. Liu et al. [123] performed an empirical study to comprehensively formalize and benchmark several prompt injection attacks and defenses. They found that the prevalent prevention-based and detection-based defense techniques are insufficient to mitigate the risks of advanced optimization-based attacks (e.g., JudgeDeceiver [185]). As a built-in safety mechanism, pre-processing-based techniques, detecting and blocking the inputs or outputs, and semantic content filtering have been employed to prevent generating undesired or inappropriate contents from LLMs through jailbreaking attacks, which could effectively mitigate potential harm [131]. Kumar et al. [103] proposed an approach to apply a safety filter on the substrings of input prompts, which provides certifiable robustness guarantees. The drawback of this approach lies in the method’s complexity, which increases proportionally with input prompt length. Wu et al. [229] propose a system-mode self-reminder to defend against jailbreaking attacks under pretending or role-playing scenarios, which can drastically reduce the jailbreaking success rate from 67.21% to 19.34%. One potential simple defense strategy is to identify the presence of “red-flagged” keywords [221], which strictly violates the usage policies of the LLM vendors, such as OpenAI [44]. Recently, Zhang et al. [262] proposed a goal prioritization technique that prioritizes generating harmless responses over helpful ones at the inference phase. This technique can significantly reduce the success rate of jailbreaking attacks in ChatGPT and Llama 2. However,
