these basic defense mechanisms may not be sufficient to prevent jailbreaking attacks with carefully crafted tricky prompts, such as privilege escalation. Furthermore, preventing these attacks still poses a significant challenge because the effective defenses may impact model utility [110]. By far, SmoothLLM is an effective defense strategy against existing jailbreaking attacks proposed by Zou et al. [276]. It can be applied for mitigating the instruction-based attacks, such as AutoDAN [118], DAN [183], and PAIR [23]. It involves a two-step process. First, copies of a specified input prompt are duplicated and perturbed. Subsequently, the outputs produced for each perturbed copy are aggregated. The desiderata encompass four key properties: attack mitigation (reduces attack success rate 100% and 50% for Llama 2 and Vicuna, respectively), non-conservatism, efficiency (in terms of computational resources), and compatibility (different LLMs). For preventing the advanced attack methods, such as MSJ [108] and MasterKey [44], an unsafe prompt detection and filtering technique may effectively refuse to provide the inappropriate response intended by the adversary. However, self-reminder-based methods [232] can create robust defenses against more complex attacks, such as DeepInception [112]. However, the efficacy of these mitigation techniques has not yet been evaluated based on these specific attack methods mentioned. Meta introduced Llama Guard, an input-output tool to safeguard LLMs [84], designed to effectively mitigate jailbreaking attacks. Llama Guard incorporates a safety risk taxonomy and the applicable policy for data collection and training. The proposed perturbation function can be further optimized over various operations, such as insertion and swapping, to make defense stronger. To defend the multi-modal prompts against jailbreaking attacks, Nie et al. [147] recently proposed DiffPure, a diffusion model based countermeasure against the visual jailbreaking examples.
Defense against Backdoor Attack. Most of the existing research, such as the removal of backdoors by fine-tuning [177], model pruning [117], and detecting backdoors by inspecting activations [24], are based on backdoor defenses in the white-box setting. Fine-mixing is a mitigation approach designed to prevent backdoors in fine-tuned LMs. It utilizes pre-trained weights through two complementary techniques: (1) a two-step fine-tuning procedure that first combines backdoored weights that have been optimized using pre-trained weights on poisoned data and then refines the combined weights on a small collection of clean data, and (2) E-PUR, an embedding purification method, which addresses potential backdoors in word embeddings [261]. CUBE utilized a density clustering algorithm called HDBSCAN to accurately discern clusters within datasets and distinguish the poisoned samples from clean data [40]. By leveraging the capabilities of HDBSCAN [135], CUBE aims to provide an effective means of differentiating clusters associated with both normal and poisoned data. Strategies to defend the backdoor attacks in the black-box setting are still lacking [95]. Perturbation-based and perplexity-based defense methods are also adopted in the literature [141, 159, 245], such as RAP, which leverages word-based robustness-aware perturbation to identify poisoned samples [245], and ONION, which eliminates trigger words via empirical analysis of sentence perplexities [159]. These two methods can potentially be applied to defend against manually designed backdoor triggers such as ProAttack [264]. Masking-differential prompt (MDP) serves as an efficient, lightweight, and adaptable defense method against backdoor attacks in prompt-based language models, particularly in few-shot learning settings [235]. MDP exploits the observation that poisoned samples exhibit increased sensitivity to random masking compared to clean samples. When the trigger is (partially) masked, the language modeling probability of a poisoned sample tends to exhibit significant variations. However, MDP may be less effective on other PLMs (e.g., GPT-3 [17]) and NLP tasks (e.g., paraphrasing). Moreover, further studies can be performed to evaluate the performance of random masking-based defenses in PLMs when the available data are even scarcer (e.g., one or zero-shot settings [207, 213]). Again, MDP was proven to be effective for the earlier backdoor attacks; however, it might not safeguard
