some advanced attacks such as BadPrompt [18] and BToP [239]. Leveraging techniques such as knowledge distillation [76], outlier-filtering [239], and fine-pruning [117] requires further exploration to mitigate the impacts of backdoor attacks. To defend against clean label backdoor triggers, such as LLMBkd [251], a trigger classification approach called REACT [251] has been performed significantly better than ONION [159] and RAP [245]. For the reasoning-based backdoor attacks, such as BadChain [236], shuffling model input might be a potential defense mechanism. Further, backdoor detection (CBD) [237], including backdoor patterns in training data to ensure robustness (RAB) [220] can be used to prevent backdoor attacks. Detecting anomalies in input data and parameter decontamination are also used to prevent the attacks executed during the training or fine-tuning phase, such as BadAgent [217]. Although these defense techniques are primarily proposed for detecting backdoors and mitigating the effects of attacks, most of them are evaluated either for LMs or in other domains (e.g., computer vision). The impact of these mitigation techniques has not yet been evaluated on recently evolved LLMs, such as GPT-4, and Llama 3.
Defense against Data Poisoning Attack. Few solutions exist to defend against poisoning attacks in LLMs. In general, data validation, filtering, cleaning, and anomaly detection techniques have been used to protect ML models from poisoning attacks [154]. A detection and filtering approach was designed to identify and filter poisoned data which is collected for performing supervised learning [12]. Empirical analysis has demonstrated that limiting the number of training epochs is a straightforward method for LMs to reduce the impact of data poisoning such as RoBERTa [209]. Identifying poison samples using perplexity can be another technique for small GPT-2 models [162] for sentiment analysis tasks. However, it may not identify poisons effectively; specifically, after inspecting the training data, more than half of the poisoned examples may remain unidentified. Filtering poisoned samples during training is also used in LMs to defend against data poisoning attacks [210]. Yan et al. [242] proposed a framework called ParaFuzz for poisoned sample detection for NLP models that leverages the interpretability of model predictions. The poisoned data points are often outliers in the training data distribution. Compared to benign training data, a model requires more time to learn the features of poisoned data. To defend against trojaning attacks in LMs (e.g., TROJANLM [258]), one possible defense technique is to adopt existing techniques from other domains such as images (e.g., STRIP [63]), detecting trigger-embedded inputs at inference phase [24, 33], and finding suspicious LMs and retrieving triggers during the model evaluation phase [27, 211]. Dataset curation techniques, such as removing near-duplicate poisoned samples, known triggers and payloads, and identifying anomalies, can help defend against manually inserted poisoned samples in training data [37]. These methods are potentially effective against poisoning attacks, such as you auto-complete me [172], AutoPoison [189], and TrojanPuzzle attack [4]. Finepruning can also be used as a defense against these attacks [117]. For the white-box attacks such as AgentPoison [29], perplexity filtering and query rephrasing [103] are utilized in the literature. Again, advanced attacks, such as NightShade [15], need advanced defense methods. While the mentioned defense strategies are mostly designed for LMs, some of them can be potentially applied to LLMs too. However, it still needs in-depth research to develop efficient defense methods against data poisoning attacks. Therefore, it requires effective defense methods that can make tradeoffs between model utility and the capability of protecting LLMs from data poisoning attacks.
6.2 Defense against Privacy Attacks on LLMs
Defense against Gradient Leakage Attack. There are several mitigation strategies to defend against gradient-based attack methods in LMs, such as random noise insertion to the gradients [224], DP [1, 65], and homomorphic encryption [10]. DP is the most common and effective technique to mitigate the effect of gradient leakage attacks in DNNs. The fundamental idea of using DP is to add a controlled amount of noise to the model updates during training, which limits the
ACM Comput. Surv., Vol. 57, No. 6, Article 152. Publication date: February 2025.


152:20 B. C. Das et al.
model’s ability to memorize and reproduce original sequences from the training data [86]. Building upon prior research on vision model attacks [224, 273], the defense mechanisms involving the addition of Gaussian or Laplacian noise to gradients and DP-SGD (Stochastic Gradient Descent) coupled with additional clipping [1] may provide an effective defense against gradient leakage attacks. For example, DP can efficiently mitigate the impact of TAB [86] by reducing the number of unique training sequences leaked by Transformer-based LMs. TAB depends on black-box access to the model—that is, the model’s top-k predictions at each token position given an input prefix. Ensuring no access to the model’s underlying probability distributions through API hardening techniques [86] may potentially mitigate the impact of such attacks. Moreover, the attack strategy for successfully reconstructing private training data may differ between well-trained models and inadequately trained models. An effective mitigation technique could involve robust model optimization during training so that adversarial perturbations have minimum impact [256]. However, DP may sacrifice the model’s utility to a certain extent during training. Trading off preserving privacy and model utility may raise a significant challenge for preventing gradient leakage attacks against LLMs. Existing works explored various techniques (e.g., [81, 163, 230]) to defend against gradient leakage attacks in the language domain for small NLP models. Extensive research is required to develop defense mechanisms against gradient leakage attacks on LLMs.
Defense against MIA To mitigate MIA in the language domain, several mechanisms are proposed, including dropout, auto-identification [204], model stacking, DP [1], and adversarial regularization [144]. Salem et al. [170] came up with the first effective defense mechanism against MIA. Their approach included dropout and model stacking. In each training iteration of a fully connected neural network model, dropout is defined as the random deletion of a certain proportion of neuron connections. It can mitigate overfitting in DNNs, which is a contributing factor to MIA [170]. However, this technique works only when a neural network is targeted by the attack model. To work with other target models, they proposed another defense technique referred to as model stacking. To defend against black-box MIA on ML models, Jia et al. [91] proposed MemGuard, which is essentially a noise perturbation mechanism for the predicted confidence score of the target model. However, this technique has been evaluated for image and numeric datasets. The performance of this technique on LMs/LLMs still remains unexplored, which necessitates further studies to evaluate whether it can effectively defend against MIA for LMs/LLMs. DP-based techniques are also widely used to prevent privacy leakage by MIA [111, 133]. Models facilitated with DP employed with the SGD optimization algorithm [51] can reduce empirical privacy leakages while ensuring comparable model utility in the non-DP environment [87]. Model pruning [71] and knowledge distillation [76] are employed to mitigate the impacts of preference-based MIA, such as PREMIA [55]. A recent framework, InferDPT [201], has been proposed to leverage black-box LLMs to facilitate privacy-preserving inference, which effectively integrates DP in text generation tasks. Another potential defense method against MIAs is regularization, which refers to a set of techniques used to prevent overfitting and improve the generalization performance of an ML model. Label smoothing [197] is one kind of regularization method that prevents overfitting of the ML model, which contributes to MIA [250]. Very few defense techniques have been proposed for LLMs [60, 111]. Most of the existing defense techniques have been experimented on relatively small LMs, such as test classifiers [214], which are not evaluated for LLMs. Moreover, DP-based defenses may impair model utility. We argue that there is a pressing need for further research studies to develop effective defense techniques against MIA on LLMs.
Defenses against PII Leakage Attacks. To mitigate the leaking of personal information from PLMs due to memorization [20], there are several general techniques. During the pre-processing phase, the process of de-duplication and training data curation [37] has the potential to
