ersary’s access to white-box information, such as gradients, it can leverage this extra information to efficiently recover more private training instances more accurately [45]. This expanded access can facilitate various privacy attacks, including attribute inference attacks, embedding inversion, MIA, and gradient leakage attacks. Availing the white-box information of a model for an adversary is sometimes impractical in real-world practice. However, most of the existing privacy attacks are designed for vision models. A limited number of studies have reported gradient leakage attacks specifically on LMs, such as the LAMP attack [11]. The evaluation dataset for some attacks (e.g., ProPILE) was built solely from private information available in open source datasets provided by major corporations, ensuring ethical data acquisition [100]. However, it is crucial to note that the heuristic data collection process might potentially lead to instances of bias, disassociation, or noise. This adds uncertainty and potential inaccuracies in the benchmark
