dataset, requiring attention when interpreting the results. Furthermore, most attack methods (e.g., BadGPT, BadPrompt, and trojaning attacks) described in the existing studies are designed for only relatively small NLP models. Only a few are tested on LLMs (e.g., ProPILE, DAN, and JAILBREAKER). In addition, the high cost of accessing commercialized LLMs, such as GPT-3.5 or upper versions, contributes to the lack of attack evaluations on LLMs. Besides, the in-depth vulnerability analysis in terms of privacy attacks and security issues is still lacking for LLMs. As well, in the FL environment, it requires very high computational power to train LLMs with such large datasets [195]. It is an open research challenge to develop effective attack and robust defense methods along with the proper evaluation metrics for LLMs. Due to the knowledge gaps, for instance, missing or outdated information might always be present in LLMs. The correctness of LLM-generated content has remained a key concern. The problem of hallucination in LLMs has been investigated and evaluated from the knowledge gap perspective; however, it is yet to be investigated from other perspectives, such as safety (i.e., abstaining from generating harmful content) [22]. For LLMs, future research should examine the applicability of well-established attack methods from other domains, such as computer vision. In addition to existing methods, novel attack techniques should be developed to rigorously inspect various vulnerabilities of LLMs, potentially targeting multiple objectives with a single attack approach. Moreover, special attention should be given to developing appropriate metrics for evaluating the impact of vulnerabilities related to security and privacy attacks in LLMs. Explainable AI (XAI) can play a vital role in this domain by increasing transparency and explainability within attack systems, allowing for a better understanding of LLM vulnerabilities. Developing XAI techniques to enhance the interpretability of LLM vulnerabilities is another essential research direction for advancing the security and privacy of LLMs.
Existing Defense Mechanisms, Challenges, and Future Research Directions. To mitigate vulnerabilities posed by security and privacy attacks, various defense techniques have been proposed in existing research. Instruction defense [171], paraphrasing [88], and re-tokenization [88] methods are commonly employed to defend against prompt injection attacks. To prevent jailbreaking attacks, SmoothLLM [168], LLM Guard [5], and perplexity filtering [66] are widely used. Data curation techniques [243], including filtering poisoned content [210] and detecting trigger-embedded inputs [24], are frequently used to mitigate data poisoning attacks and backdoor attacks. However, DP-SGD [1] is a common approach to defend against gradient leakage attacks, MIAs, and PII leakage attacks. In particular, noise perturbation [273] is a popular strategy to defend against gradient leakage attacks. Model pruning [117] and knowledge distillation [76] are also utilized to defend MIAs. To prevent PII leakage attacks, training data curation [243] and restricting attacker access to training data, or a model [86], serve as viable countermeasures. For defense, although ChatGPT’s safety protocols are typically robust enough to prevent singlestep jailbreaking prompts, vulnerabilities still remain for MSJ [108]. Inspired by the reasoning processes of LLMs, system-mode self-reminder techniques have emerged as potential defense [235]. While drawbacks of self-reminder have been explored in user queries across various NLP tasks, assessing its impact across all types of user interactions remains challenging, complicating the evaluation of its influence on overall user experience [229]. Considering these shortcomings, developing more flexible self-reminding systems that improve safety, trustworthiness, and accountability in LLMs without compromising effectiveness is a research challenge to protect LLMs from jailbreaking attacks. Furthermore, individuals with malicious intent are highly active in online forums, discussing new strategies. It is essential to conduct further research to identify and implement effective defense strategies to mitigate the risks posed by the latest jailbreaking attacks. Efficient strategies to prevent backdoor attacks in a black-box environment are still lacking [95].
