Moreover, prompt-based PLMs are susceptible to textual backdoor attacks [49, 239]. Addressing the challenge of textual backdoor attacks in prompt-based paradigms, such as the few-shot learning [218], is another challenge. MDP [235] faces challenges in various NLP tasks, such as paraphrasing and sentence similarity [62]. Its performance under few-shot learning remains uncertain due to a lack of practical evaluation. While MDP has shown strength against earlier backdoor attacks, it may not be effective against more recent attacks, such as BadPrompt [18] and BToP [239]. Perplexity-based methods and filtering-based methods may not work well when attackers use synonymous trigger keys [80]. Furthermore, developing dynamic defense methods that consider the preceding factors is a challenging task for the future. Currently, the predominant focus of investigation on backdoor attacks revolves around text classification in LLMs. However, a significant gap exists in the literature concerning investigations into mitigation to backdoor attacks on various tasks for which LLMs find widespread application, such as text summarization and text generation [244]. For poisoning attacks, there is not yet effective mitigation for ProAttack [264] and BadPrompt [18]. Defense techniques, such as dataset cleaning and removing near duplicate poisoned samples and anomalies, may slow down the model development process to defend against data poisoning attacks. Other defense methods, such as stopping training after certain epochs, achieve a moderate defense against poisoning attacks but degrade the model utility [210]. Gradient perturbation [78] and DP-SGD-based methods [1] are frequently used to defend against privacy attacks in LLMs. However, a recent study has demonstrated that adding a standard level of random noise into the gradient update might not always work well to prevent gradient leakage attacks on medical images [42]. An open language model (OLMo) has been introduced to provide access to the data, code, and model [191] to facilitate open research on LMs. While adhering to established practices for obscuring PII exposure and removing toxic content, the approach lacks explicit discussion of attack impacts and risk mitigation explored in this survey. Future research could leverage secure multi-party computation [39] to counter privacy attacks. Future research initiatives for enhancing security and privacy in LLMs can be directed toward several key areas. An ideal defense method should be able to effectively achieve a balance between model utility and security and privacy protection. The development of real-time privacy monitoring systems is essential to improve the resilience of privacy-preserving LLMs. This necessitates the exploration of robust detection techniques against various security and privacy attacks. Furthermore, a thorough evaluation of less-explored defense techniques, such as secure multi-party computation, is necessary to assess their effectiveness against LLM vulnerabilities. Finally, leveraging the capabilities of XAI can improve transparency in LLM defense mechanisms.
Role of XAI in Enhancing Security and Privacy of LLMs. The LLM’s ability to make decisions on various learning tasks is often criticized due to its black-box nature (e.g., non-interpretable weights). It makes it more challenging for the new practitioners and developers of this field, as it hinders their ability to clearly interpret and understand its application, particularly in critical cases. XAI can help to bridge this gap by developing methods to interpret and explain complex LLM systems, the decision-making process, and outputs [19]. Conducting studies and research to build explainable methods is highly essential to make the usage of LLMs more reliable and trustworthy. XAI can provide transparent insights into the inference process and the dynamic weight assignment by the attention mechanism of the LLMs, which enhances interpretability by highlighting the most influential input features that contribute to its predictions. This explainability makes the model more trustworthy and ensures that its output is explainable. XAI has shown its potential in several real-world AI applications, such as cybersecurity [169] and enhancing data privacy [53]. In ML, several techniques exist, such as LIME (Local I nterpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) [167] and SHAP (SH apley Additive exPlanations) [126], which offer insights into model behavior
